Standard 3a--Universal Foundation Skills Intermediate
Basic Skills 1.
Basic skills include the ability to read, write, listen, and speak as well as perform arithmetical and mathematical functions.
Students: Â· listen to and read the ideas of others and analyze what they hear and read; acquire and use information from a variety of sources; and apply a combination of mathematical operations to solve problems in oral or written form.
This is evident, for example, when students: v follow directions that involve a series of actions v locate and use information on a wide range of topics from many different sources v present an oral report to the class after investigating several career clusters v record data and prepare a graph on the movement of the stock market or a particular stock v explore ways in which geometry is used in everyday life v solve basic problems involving integers, fractions, and decimals.
Thinking Skills 2.
Thinking skills lead to problem solving, experimenting, and focused observation and allow the application of knowledge to new and unfamiliar situations.
Students: Â· evaluate facts, solve advanced problems, and make decisions by applying logic and reasoning skills.
This is evident, for example, when students: v describe the best method to evaluate customer interest in the establishment of a new product line for a business v describe the best method to evaluate student interest in the establishment of a new school sport or club v create a work schedule to ensure equity in employee hours and days worked v sequence facts in a logical order to solve a problem.
