Basic Skills 1.
Basic skills include the ability to read, write, listen, and speak as well as perform arithmetical and mathematical functions.
Students: Â· use a combination of techniques to read or listen to complex information and analyze what they hear or read; convey information confidently and coherently in written or oral form; and analyze and solve mathematical problems requiring use of multiple computational skills.
This is evident, for example, when students: v gather and use information presented in print and electronic sources to create a research report and database v examine a case study to evaluate whether the information contained within it is adequate to support generalizations about the topic v participate in debates, interviews, and panel discussions v use word processing and desktop publishing software to present information on a sales campaign v analyze a company's balance sheet and income statement for industry-recognized ratios for assets, liabilities, and net income/loss v order and price inventory appropriately as part of a work experience program.
