Thinking skills lead to problem solving, experimenting, and focused observation and allow the application of knowledge to new and unfamiliar situations.
Students: Â· demonstrate the ability to organize and process information and apply skills in new ways.
This is evident, for example, when students: v provide examples of ways to alter a work schedule to allow for more job sharing among two or more employees v evaluate a variety of options suggested, select an option, explain the reason for the selection, and provide the strategies for implementation v recognize a problem and design steps to solve the problem v prepare and present a report on how knowledge gained from one content area helped solve a problem in another area.
