Standard 3b--Career Majors Core
Business/Information Systems 1.
Basic Business Understanding Students: Â· demonstrate an understanding of business, marketing, and multinational economic concepts, perform business-related mathematical computations, and analyze/interpret business-related numerical information.
This is evident, for example, when students: v explain the meaning of basic business and global economic terms v provide examples of typical problems (e.g., declining sales, outdated hardware) that could arise in a business and explain how steps in the decision-making process could be used to solve such problems v use spreadsheet software to forecast expenses for a business for three consecutive years v interpret a 10-year graph of the Gross National Product (GNP) or Gross Domestic Product (GDP) v demonstrate an understanding of basic international business concepts v identify and locate major cities and trade regions throughout the world.
This is evident, for example, when students: v compose and produce simple business documents (e.g., letters, memos, reports) v prepare and deliver a three-minute oral presentation using at least one visual aid (e.g., marketing research report, stock market analysis) v identify and interpret positive/negative facial expressions and other body language indicators v identify and explain how and why specialized communication tools are used (e.g., voice mail, electronic mail, beepers, pagers) v use simple electronic databases and spreadsheet information systems to manage a membership list or prepare a payroll ledger v recognize challenges in business related to people speaking various languages v identify international cultural similarities and differences and explain their relationship to international trade.
3.
Information Management/Communication Students: Â· prepare, maintain, interpret/analyze, and transmit/ distribute information in a variety of formats while demonstrating the oral, nonverbal, and written communication skills essential for working in today's international service-/information-/technological-based economy.
2.
Business-Related Technology Students: Â· select, apply, and troubleshoot hardware and software used in the processing of business transactions.
This is evident, for example, when students: v use touch keyboarding techniques to produce business documents (e.g., letters, memorandums, reports) v use the components of various business technologies (e.g., CPU, disk drive, CD-ROM, modem, fax machine, scanner) v enter data into various technological systems, using a variety of input devices (e.g., handwriting, keyboard, mouse, scanner, voice recognition) v produce business documents and reports, using appropriate technology (e.g., business letter/word processing; business graphs and charts/spreadsheet and graphics software; inventory control reports/hand-held bar code scanners) v use word processing software to prepare a form letter and do a mail merge soliciting customers for a simulated business v use electronic media (e.g., e-mail, Internet/World Wide Web, fax) to communicate internationally.
STANDARD 3b
4.
Business Systems Students: Â· demonstrate an understanding of the interrelatedness of business, social, and economic systems/subsystems.
This is evident, for example, when students: v identify and explain the social, organizational, economic, business, and technological systems that stimulated the transition from an agricultural-based economy through an industrial-based economy to the current service-/information/technological-based economy v identify and explain aspects of basic systems that typically function in a business enterprise (e.g., administrative, financial, marketing) v diagram the components (input, processing, output, feedback) of a typical business system and explain what documents/materials/products are used in each component (e.g., billing, legal, marketing) v explain and provide examples of the interrelationship of the free enterprise system and the marketing concept v identify basic features of the sole proprietorship, partnership, corporation, and franchise systems, and decide which form of organization would be best for given situations v identify the currency systems of major countries and calculate currency exchange transactions.
Key ideas are identified by numbers (1).
Performance indicators are identified by bullets (Â·).
Sample tasks are identified by triangles (v).
18
Students who choose a career major will acquire the career-specific technical knowledge/skills necessary to progress toward gainful employment, career advancement, and success in postsecondary programs.
Core
5.
Resource Management Students: Â· identify, organize, plan, and allocate resources (e.g., financial, materials/facilities, human, time) in demonstrating the ability to manage their lives as learners, contributing family members, globally competitive workers, and self-sufficient individuals.
This is evident, for example, when students: v explain the need for and the steps incurred by a business in setting goals and priorities to meet company objectives v identify and discuss the process for constructing a simple operating budget for a specific purpose in a small business (e.g., advertising budget) v list and explain various personal and business needs related to banking, investments, and insurance (e.g., personal checkbook, mutual funds, life insurance) v explain various paycheck deductions (e.g., federal and State taxes, FICA) v open and use personal savings and checking accounts v assist Red Cross personnel in scheduling student volunteers for participation in a local blood donor event.
6.
Interpersonal Dynamics Students: Â· exhibit interpersonal skills essential for success in the multinational business world, demonstrate basic leadership abilities/skills, and function effectively as members of a work group or team.
This is evident, for example, when students: v outline essential personal attributes/attitudes for successful interpersonal relationships (e.g., appearance/cleanliness, integrity, punctuality, dedication/commitment) v explain the many benefits inherent in a business with a culturally diverse workforce v demonstrate an understanding of how the traditions of various major cultures affect international business practices v use a case study to illustrate how a business might use a team approach, flextime, or job sharing in its daily operations v list the key elements necessary to facilitate a business-related meeting v teach a classmate how to reconcile a checking account or how to use telecommunications software v participate in a job interview.
STANDARD 3b
19
Standard 3b--Career Majors Specialized
Business/Information Systems 1.
Basic Business Understanding Students: Â· demonstrate an understanding of business, marketing, and multinational economic concepts, perform business-related mathematical computations, and analyze/interpret business-related numerical information.
This is evident, for example, when students: v explain and interpret advanced business and economics terms associated with their occupational cluster of study (e.g., reading and interpreting articles in business publications) v develop a viable solution(s) for a case problem in a business simulation v conduct a research project and make a presentation illustrating how the "law of supply and demand" applies to the local community v use accounting or spreadsheet software to prepare an income statement and balance sheet for a simulated service business v use appropriate software to produce several types of graphs (e.g., bar, pie) of the operating budget for the school district, the school store, or a local business for each of the past five years and provide an analysis of the financial trends v describe the impact of international business activities on the local, regional, national, and international economies.
This is evident, for example, when students: v compose/produce a multipage, complex business memorandum or business sales letter v prepare and deliver a persuasive sales presentation and effectively handle customer questions and objections in a simulated situation v use specialized communication tools, such as voice and electronic mail systems, at typical business productivity standards v participate in a panel discussion on a business topic which will be critiqued for communication effectiveness v analyze the effectiveness of individuals communicating in an international business environment, given a specific situation.
3.
Information Management/Communication Students: Â· prepare, maintain, interpret/analyze, and transmit/ distribute information in a variety of formats while demonstrating the oral, nonverbal, and written communication skills essential for working in today's international service-/information-/technological-based economy.
4.
Business Systems Students: Â· demonstrate an understanding of the interrelatedness of business, social, and economic systems/subsystems.
This is evident, for example, when students: v analyze the effects that changes in internal and external influences (e.g., human resources, suppliers, government, technology, customs/traditions) have on various business systems v identify, describe, and diagram systems and subsystems associated with typical businesses in the occupational cluster of study v plan, implement, analyze, and modify systems and subsystems for a student-operated school store or business in which students are employed v describe the international monetary system, including the International Monetary Fund, World Bank, and Eurocurrencies.
2.
Business-Related Technology Students: Â· select, apply, and troubleshoot hardware and software used in the processing of business transactions.
