Personal Qualities Students: Â· demonstrate the skills necessary to function and interact effectively in a variety of settings within the arts/humanities.
This is evident, for example, when students: v work collaboratively in leadership roles and as members of a team v provide evidence of high personal standards through exhibitions, performances or portfolios that are recognized as excellent by the profession v display diligence and perseverance in the face of unpleasant tasks v demonstrate adaptable, cooperative, empathetic, enthusiastic, eqalitarian, polite, and responsible behavior in a work group or job setting v understand the range of possibilities within the career field, determine where their skills and abilities fit within that range, and make plans for further study v practice creative approaches to conflict resolution v show behaviors that comply with social, legal, and ethical requirements of the arts, broadcasting, journalism, and publishing v exemplify positive attitudes toward their work, the workplace, and authority figures.
5.
Creative Processes and Practices Students: Â· demonstrate a repertoire of experience when presenting an exhibition, performance, portfolio, or publication.
This is evident, for example, when students: v decide upon direction for a new body of work based on a review and reflection on their portfolio v create a product that crosses traditional disciplines, integrating knowledge acquired in school, at work, or at home v clarify ideas by comparing and contrasting, classifying, sequencing, uncovering assumptions, reasoning and drawing conclusions, comprehending part/whole relationships v create original works that demonstrate that they are adventurous, courageous, curious, imaginative, independent, and inventive v defend and/or explain their creative process, practice, and product v generate alternative possibilities and solutions to a real life problem v utilize their portfolios and journals as a means for perpetual self-assessment and the ultimate attainment of current workplace standards.
6.
Making Results Public Students: Â· create an ongoing portfolio that demonstrates the competencies and creative processes delineated in the preceding key ideas.
This is evident, for example, when students: v develop a commencement portfolio containing evidence of creative growth and mastery of entry level occupational skills v produce a professional quality literary/art magazine using a variety of skills: layout, typography, editing, paste-up, proofreading, illustration, photography v produce a professional quality news magazine broadcast that combines research, sequencing, and interpretive skills v create and/or produce a professional quality theatrical production using a repertoire of skills: improvisation, scene work, character development, costume, stage and lighting, funding, marketing, promoting v display original art, craft, design, graphics, manuscripts, poetry or scores in a library or other public setting v create and produce a professional standard dance performance using a repertoire of skills: choreography, costume, lighting, and stage design, directing, marketing and promotion v create and produce a professional standard musical event, using a repertoire of skills: performing, funding, marketing, promotion v create and produce a professional standard art exhibition using a repertoire of skills: mounting, curating, hanging, labeling, lighting, funding, marketing and promotion.
STANDARD 3b
51
52
Samples of Student Work The samples of student work included in this section are intended to begin the process of articulating the performance standards at each level of achievement.
This collection is not yet adequate for that purpose in either numbers or scope of examples.
As New York State continues to collect work samples from the schools for inclusion in the document, we expect a much clearer understanding of the performance standards to be evident.
Neither are these samples presented as models of excellence.
They vary in degree of achievement.
Some are "acceptable"; others "more proficient."
All are meant to provide examples of the kind of work students might produce to demonstrate progress toward the standard.
